comments.body:
Follow-up after #11 and #12: I would not add another text PR until those settle, but two concrete next work items seem useful.

1. Implementation-evidence checklist

A useful small appendix or implementation-facing note could separate the evidence an implementation can actually produce from the abstract security argument:

- negotiated group evidence: the implementation can show that the selected group was the intended hybrid or standalone group;
- component-presence evidence: for hybrid groups, both ECDHE and ML-KEM inputs are present and accepted before key schedule input;
- transcript-binding evidence: the accepted key exchange inputs are bound to the same handshake transcript and negotiated group;
- failure-path evidence: malformed shares, missing components, wrong group, transcript mismatch, and silent fallback fail closed;
- observability evidence: logs, traces, APIs, or test harnesses can distinguish a real hybrid acceptance from a fallback or partial acceptance.

This could stay explicitly non-normative and implementation-facing, so it does not turn the memo into a test-suite document.

2. Cost-measurement plan

For the cost discussion, I think the cleanest next step is to avoid a conclusion and instead define what would need to be measured:

- wire bytes at full TLS-handshake granularity, not only key_share fields;
- ClientHello / ServerHello size, record boundaries, fragmentation, and retry behavior;
- CPU and memory under representative endpoint classes;
- implementation complexity: code paths that remain necessary for compatibility, policy, and fallback;
- operational rollout cost: deployment class, endpoint control, monitoring, and interop/debugging burden.

This would let the document say "cost needs evidence by deployment class" without asserting that standalone ML-KEM is or is not cheaper in general.

I would wait for #11/#12 feedback before turning either into another PR, to avoid creating overlapping text churn.

